'''Ōtori Shrine''' (大鷲神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}} located in {{ill|Adachi|ja|足立区}}, Tokyo. It serves as the {{ill|Ujigami|ja|産土神}} (guardian deity) of the Hanahata area and is also known as '''Hanahata Ōtori Shrine''' (花畑大鷲神社). It is considered the origin of the well-known {{ill|Tori-no-Ichi|ja|酉の市}} markets, with its head shrine being {{ill|Ōtori Taisha|ja|大鳥大社}}. The shrine is featured in the {{ill|Edo Meisho Zue|ja|江戸名所図会}}.{{sfn|Edo Meisho Zue|1927|p=521}}

== Overview ==

Surrounded by old and large trees, the shrine is situated in a serene environment teeming with various seasonal flora and fauna. Though typically tranquil, it attracts many visitors during {{ill|Hatsumōde|ja|初詣}} (New Year’s visits) and {{ill|Shichi-Go-San|ja|七五三}} celebrations in November. During the nights of {{ill|Tori-no-Ichi|ja|酉の市}}, fireworks are displayed.

The shrine also preserves records of mathematical tablets ({{ill|Sangaku|ja|算額}}) dedicated by local Edo-period mathematicians. Among these, the "Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Sangaku," donated by Kanesugi Kiyotoki’s disciples in 1833, is registered as a tangible cultural property of Adachi Ward.{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.adachi.tokyo.jp/bunka/chiikibunka/bunkazai_ootorijinjasangaku.html|title=Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Sangaku|publisher=Adachi Ward|accessdate=2022-08-22}}

== History ==

=== Origins ===
The shrine's founding is attributed to the {{ill|Hōji|ja|宝治}} period (1247–1249).{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1978|p=231}} It is said that during the {{ill|Later Three-Year War|ja|後三年の役}}, the Heian-period military commander {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshimitsu|ja|源義光}} prayed for victory at this location after witnessing an eagle. This marked the shrine’s establishment.{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1992|p=162}}

Initially referred to as {{ill|Ōtori Daimyōjin|ja|鷲明神}}, the shrine was renamed Ōtori Shrine following the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離}} during the Meiji era. 

* The shrine is mentioned in a {{ill|Kōda|ja|棟札}} dated to the first year of {{ill|Kan’ei|ja|寛永}} (1624), indicating its existence prior to this date.
* The oldest extant stone artifacts date back to the second year of {{ill|Manji|ja|万治}} (1659).
* During the {{ill|Shinbutsu shūgō|ja|神仏習合}} period, the shrine’s affiliated temple was {{ill|Shōkaku-in|ja|正覚院}}.
* The current shrine structure dates back to the Ansei era, with contributions from the {{ill|Kubota Domain|ja|久保田藩}}’s Satake family. Its wooden columns feature carvings attributed to a disciple of {{ill|Hidari Jingorō|ja|左甚五郎}}.

=== Deity ===
While {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|日本武尊}} is listed as the shrine’s current deity, historical records suggest that {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshimitsu|ja|源義光}} was likely its original object of worship. The shrine received significant patronage from the Satake family and other clans claiming descent from Yoshimitsu.

== Events ==

* **Third Sunday of July** ({{ill|Marine Day|ja|海の日}}): {{ill|Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Lion Dance|ja|花畑大鷲神社獅子舞}} (designated an intangible cultural property of Adachi Ward). The shrine’s {{ill|Three-Lion Dance|ja|三匹獅子舞}} is performed.{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1978|p=232}}
* {{ill|Tori-no-Ichi|ja|酉の市}}

== Access ==
* A 27-minute walk from {{ill|Yatsuka Station|ja|谷塚駅}} on the {{ill|Tōbu Isesaki Line|ja|東武伊勢崎線}} ({{OSM route map|start=35.81411,139.80140|goal=35.80924,139.82021|name=Route}}).

