The shrine's founding is attributed to the {{ill|Hōji|ja|宝治|12=draft|12=draft}} period (1247–1249).{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1978|p=231}} It is said that during the {{ill|Later Three-Year War|ja|後三年の役|12=draft|12=draft}}, the Heian-period military commander {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshimitsu|ja|源義光|12=draft|12=draft}} prayed for victory at this location after witnessing an eagle. This marked the shrine’s establishment.{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1992|p=162}}

Initially referred to as {{ill|Ōtori Daimyōjin|ja|鷲明神|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine was renamed Ōtori Shrine following the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|12=draft|12=draft}} during the Meiji era. 

* The shrine is mentioned in a {{ill|Kōda|ja|棟札|12=draft|12=draft}} dated to the first year of {{ill|Kan’ei|ja|寛永|12=draft|12=draft}} (1624), indicating its existence prior to this date.
* The oldest extant stone artifacts date back to the second year of {{ill|Manji|ja|万治|12=draft|12=draft}} (1659).
* During the {{ill|Shinbutsu shūgō|ja|神仏習合|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō|12=draft|12=draft}} period, the shrine’s affiliated temple was {{ill|Shōkaku-in|ja|正覚院|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* The current shrine structure dates back to the Ansei era, with contributions from the {{ill|Kubota Domain|ja|久保田藩|12=draft|12=draft}}’s Satake family. Its wooden columns feature carvings attributed to a disciple of {{ill|Hidari Jingorō|ja|左甚五郎|12=draft|12=draft}}.

=== deity ===
While {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|日本武尊|1=Yamato Takeru|lt=Prince Yamato Takeru|3=ヤマトタケル|12=draft|12=draft}} is listed as the shrine’s current deity, historical records suggest that {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshimitsu|ja|源義光|12=draft|12=draft}} was likely its original object of worship. The shrine received significant patronage from the Satake family and other clans claiming descent from Yoshimitsu.

== Events ==

* '''Third Sunday of July''' ({{ill|Marine Day|ja|海の日|12=draft|12=draft}}): {{ill|Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Lion Dance|ja|花畑大鷲神社獅子舞|12=draft|12=draft}} (designated an intangible cultural property of Adachi Ward). The shrine’s {{ill|Three-Lion Dance|ja|三匹獅子舞|12=draft|12=draft}} is performed.{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1978|p=232}}
* {{ill|Tori-no-Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|12=draft|12=draft}}

== Access ==
* A 27-minute walk from {{ill|Yatsuka Station|ja|谷塚駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Tōbu Isesaki Line|ja|東武伊勢崎線|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{OSM route map|start=35.81411,139.80140|goal=35.80924,139.82021|name=Route}}).

