'''Ōtori Shrine''' (大鷲神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Adachi|ja|足立区|12=draft|12=draft}}, Tokyo. It serves as the {{ill|Ujigami|ja|産土神|1=Ubusunagami|12=draft|12=draft}} (guardian deity) of the Hanahata area and is also known as '''Hanahata Ōtori Shrine''' (花畑大鷲神社). It is considered the origin of the well-known {{ill|Tori-no-Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|12=draft|12=draft}} markets, with its head shrine being {{ill|Ōtori Taisha|ja|大鳥大社|1=Ōtori taisha|12=draft|12=draft}}. The shrine is featured in the {{ill|Edo meisho zue|ja|江戸名所図会|12=draft|12=draft}}.{{sfn|Edo Meisho Zue|1927|p=521}}

== Overview ==

Surrounded by old and large trees, the shrine is situated in a serene environment teeming with various seasonal flora and fauna. Though typically tranquil, it attracts many visitors during {{ill|Hatsumōde|ja|初詣|12=draft|12=draft}} (New Year’s visits) and {{ill|Shichi-Go-San|ja|七五三|12=draft|12=draft}} celebrations in November. During the nights of {{ill|Tori-no-Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|12=draft|12=draft}}, fireworks are displayed.

The shrine also preserves records of mathematical tablets ({{ill|Sangaku|ja|算額|12=draft|12=draft}}) dedicated by local Edo-period mathematicians. Among these, the "Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Sangaku," donated by Kanesugi Kiyotoki’s disciples in 1833, is registered as a tangible cultural property of Adachi Ward.{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.adachi.tokyo.jp/bunka/chiikibunka/bunkazai_ootorijinjasangaku.html|title=Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Sangaku|publisher=Adachi Ward|accessdate=2022-08-22}}

