The shrine's founding is attributed to the {{ill|Hōji|ja|宝治|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōji|qq=}} period (1247–1249).{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1978|p=231}} It is said that during the {{ill|Later Three-Year War|ja|後三年の役|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Later Three-Year War|qq=}}, the Heian-period military commander {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshimitsu|ja|源義光|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoshimitsu|qq=}} prayed for victory at this location after witnessing an eagle. This marked the shrine’s establishment.{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1992|p=162}}

Initially referred to as {{ill|Ōtori Daimyōjin|ja|鷲明神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Daimyōjin|qq=}}, the shrine was renamed Ōtori Shrine following the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu bunri|qq=}} during the Meiji era. 

* The shrine is mentioned in a {{ill|Munafuda|ja|棟札|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōda|qq=}} dated to the first year of {{ill|Kan’ei|ja|寛永|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kan’ei|qq=}} (1624), indicating its existence prior to this date.
* The oldest extant stone artifacts date back to the second year of {{ill|Manji|ja|万治|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Manji|qq=}} (1659).
* During the {{ill|Shinbutsu shūgō|ja|神仏習合|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu shūgō|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu-shūgō|qq=}} period, the shrine’s affiliated temple was {{ill|Shōkaku-in|ja|正覚院|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōkaku-in|qq=}}.
* The current shrine structure dates back to the Ansei era, with contributions from the {{ill|Kubota Domain|ja|久保田藩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kubota Domain|qq=}}’s Satake family. Its wooden columns feature carvings attributed to a disciple of {{ill|Hidari Jingorō|ja|左甚五郎|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hidari Jingorō|qq=}}.

=== deity ===
While {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|日本武尊|1=Yamato Takeru|lt=Prince Yamato Takeru|3=ヤマトタケル|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Takeru|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Takeru|qq=}} is listed as the shrine’s current deity, historical records suggest that {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshimitsu|ja|源義光|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoshimitsu|qq=}} was likely its original object of worship. The shrine received significant patronage from the Satake family and other clans claiming descent from Yoshimitsu.

== Events ==

* '''Third Sunday of July''' ({{ill|Marine Day|ja|海の日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Marine Day|qq=}}): {{ill|Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Lion Dance|ja|花畑大鷲神社獅子舞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Lion Dance|qq=}} (designated an intangible cultural property of Adachi Ward). The shrine’s {{ill|Three-Lion Dance|ja|三匹獅子舞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Three-Lion Dance|qq=}} is performed.{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1978|p=232}}
* {{ill|Tori-no-Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori-no-Ichi|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori-no-Ichi|qq=}}

== Access ==
* A 27-minute walk from {{ill|Yatsuka Station|ja|谷塚駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yatsuka Station|qq=}} on the {{ill|Tōbu Isesaki Line|ja|東武伊勢崎線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōbu Isesaki Line|qq=}} ({{OSM route map|start=35.81411,139.80140|goal=35.80924,139.82021|name=Route}}).

