'''Ōtori Shrine''' (大鷲神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in [[:en:Adachi, Tokyo|Adachi]], Tokyo. It serves as the [[:en:Ubusunagami|Ubusunagami]] (guardian deity) of the Hanahata area and is also known as '''Hanahata Ōtori Shrine''' (花畑大鷲神社). It is considered the origin of the well-known {{ill|Tori-no-Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori-no-Ichi|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori-no-Ichi|qq=}} markets, with its head shrine being [[:en:Ōtori taisha|Ōtori taisha]]. The shrine is featured in the [[:en:Edo meisho zue|Edo meisho zue]].{{sfn|Edo Meisho Zue|1927|p=521}}

== Overview ==

Surrounded by old and large trees, the shrine is situated in a serene environment teeming with various seasonal flora and fauna. Though typically tranquil, it attracts many visitors during [[:en:Hatsumōde|Hatsumōde]] (New Year’s visits) and [[:en:Shichi-Go-San|Shichi-Go-San]] celebrations in November. During the nights of {{ill|Tori-no-Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori-no-Ichi|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori-no-Ichi|qq=}}, fireworks are displayed.

The shrine also preserves records of mathematical tablets ([[:en:Sangaku|Sangaku]]) dedicated by local Edo-period mathematicians. Among these, the "Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Sangaku," donated by Kanesugi Kiyotoki’s disciples in 1833, is registered as a tangible cultural property of Adachi Ward.{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.adachi.tokyo.jp/bunka/chiikibunka/bunkazai_ootorijinjasangaku.html|title=Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Sangaku|publisher=Adachi Ward|accessdate=2022-08-22}}

== History ==

=== Origins ===
The shrine's founding is attributed to the [[:en:Hōji (era)|Hōji]] period (1247–1249).{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1978|p=231}} It is said that during the [[:en:Gosannen War|Later Three-Year War]], the Heian-period military commander [[:en:Minamoto no Yoshimitsu|Minamoto no Yoshimitsu]] prayed for victory at this location after witnessing an eagle. This marked the shrine’s establishment.{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1992|p=162}}

Initially referred to as {{ill|Ōtori Daimyōjin|ja|鷲明神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Daimyōjin|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, the shrine was renamed Ōtori Shrine following the [[:en:Shinbutsu bunri|Shinbutsu bunri]] during the Meiji era. 

* The shrine is mentioned in a {{ill|Munafuda|ja|棟札|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōda|qq=}} dated to the first year of [[:en:Kan'ei|Kan’ei]] (1624), indicating its existence prior to this date.
* The oldest extant stone artifacts date back to the second year of [[:en:Manji (era)|Manji]] (1659).
* During the [[:en:Shinbutsu-shūgō|Shinbutsu-shūgō]] period, the shrine’s affiliated temple was {{ill|Shōkaku-in|ja|正覚院|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōkaku-in|qq=|1=Shogakuin|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11545644}}.
* The current shrine structure dates back to the Ansei era, with contributions from the [[:en:Kubota Domain|Kubota Domain]]’s Satake family. Its wooden columns feature carvings attributed to a disciple of [[:en:Hidari Jingorō|Hidari Jingorō]].

=== deity ===
While {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|日本武尊|1=Yamato Takeru|lt=Prince Yamato Takeru|3=ヤマトタケル|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Takeru|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Takeru|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to ヤマトタケル|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q461258}} is listed as the shrine’s current deity, historical records suggest that [[:en:Minamoto no Yoshimitsu|Minamoto no Yoshimitsu]] was likely its original object of worship. The shrine received significant patronage from the Satake family and other clans claiming descent from Yoshimitsu.

== Events ==

* '''Third Sunday of July''' ([[:en:Marine Day|Marine Day]]): {{ill|Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Lion Dance|ja|花畑大鷲神社獅子舞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanahata Ōtori Shrine Lion Dance|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (designated an intangible cultural property of Adachi Ward). The shrine’s {{ill|Three-Lion Dance|ja|三匹獅子舞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Three-Lion Dance|qq=}} is performed.{{sfn|Adachi Historical Society|1978|p=232}}
* {{ill|Tori-no-Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori-no-Ichi|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori-no-Ichi|qq=}}

== Access ==
* A 27-minute walk from [[:en:Yatsuka Station|Yatsuka Station]] on the [[:en:Tobu Isesaki Line|Tōbu Isesaki Line]] ({{OSM route map|start=35.81411,139.80140|goal=35.80924,139.82021|name=Route}}).

